  "prompt": "How do we forget any Wi-Fi in Windows 10?",
  "response": "There are a couple of ways to forget a Wi-Fi network in Windows 10:\n\n**Method 1: Through the Settings App (Recommended)**\n\nThis is the easiest and most reliable method.\n\n1.  **Open Settings:**\n    *   Click the **Start Menu** (Windows icon) in the bottom-left corner.\n    *   Click the **Settings icon** (gear icon).  Or press **Windows Key + I**.\n\n2.  **Go to Network & Internet:**\n    *   In the Settings window, click on **Network & Internet**.\n\n3.  **Select Wi-Fi:**\n    *   In the left-hand menu, click on **Wi-Fi**.\n\n4.  **Manage Known Networks:**\n    *   Click on **Manage known networks**.\n\n5.  **Select the Network to Forget:**\n    *   A list of saved Wi-Fi networks will appear.  Find the network you want to forget.  Click on its name.\n\n6.  **Click Forget:**\n    *   Click the **Forget** button that appears below the selected network name.\n\n**Method 2: Through the Command Prompt (Less User-Friendly)**\n\nThis method is more technical and might be useful if the Settings app isn't working correctly.\n\n1.  **Open Command Prompt as Administrator:**\n    *   Click the **Start Menu**.\n    *   Type `cmd` in the search bar.\n    *   Right-click on **Command Prompt** in the search results and select **Run as administrator**.  Click **Yes** if prompted to allow changes to your device.\n\n2.  **List All Saved Wi-Fi Profiles:**\n    *   In the Command Prompt window, type the following command and press Enter:\n\n        ```\n        netsh wlan show profiles\n        ```\n\n    *   This will display a list of all the Wi-Fi networks that your computer has saved profiles for. Note the **name** of the network you want to forget *exactly* as it appears in the list (case sensitive).\n\n3.  **Delete the Wi-Fi Profile:**\n    *   Type the following command and press Enter, replacing `[Network Name]` with the *exact* name of the Wi-Fi network from the previous step:\n\n        ```\n        netsh wlan delete profile name=\"[Network Name]\"\n        ```\n\n    *   For example, if the network name is \"MyHomeWifi\", the command would be:\n\n        ```\n        netsh wlan delete profile name=\"MyHomeWifi\"\n        ```\n\n4.  **Verify Deletion (Optional):**\n    *   You can run the `netsh wlan show profiles` command again to confirm that the network has been removed from the list.\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n*   **Method 1 (Settings App):** This method provides a graphical user interface (GUI) that is user-friendly and easier to navigate.\n*   **Method 2 (Command Prompt):** This method uses command-line tools. `netsh` is a command-line scripting utility for configuring network settings.  `wlan` specifies that we are working with wireless LAN (Wi-Fi).  `show profiles` lists saved Wi-Fi profiles, and `delete profile` removes a specified profile.\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   **Administrator Privileges:**  You must run Command Prompt as an administrator for the `netsh wlan delete profile` command to work.\n*   **Network Name:** Be extremely careful when entering the network name in the Command Prompt.  The name is case-sensitive and must match the name listed in the `netsh wlan show profiles` output *exactly*.  If you misspell it, you won't delete the correct profile.\n*   **Reconnecting:** After forgetting a network, you will need to re-enter the Wi-Fi password if you want to connect to it again.\n*   **VPN Profiles:**  The above methods only remove the Wi-Fi network profile. If you've also configured a VPN profile related to that network, you might need to remove that VPN connection separately through the Settings app (Network & Internet > VPN).\n",
